lasgow</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>G12 8QQ</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Scotland</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>COLLABORATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/94C8C4DB-4B2C-4313-A1A2-EB6C358E7587"><gtr:id>94C8C4DB-4B2C-4313-A1A2-EB6C358E7587</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Miriam</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Meyerhoff</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH008020%2F1"><gtr:id>0BF55870-4219-4F76-AE34-480F9445E80A</gtr:id><gtr:title>Summer School of Sociolinguistics 2010</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H008020/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>A six-day Summer School teaching master classes and affording PG students the opportunity to present their own work was held at the University of Edinburgh in June 2010. Leading researchers from the UK and North America gave state of the art lectures on their sub-disciplines in sociolinguistics, ran three-hour workshops focussing on methods for data collection and data analysis in sociolinguistics, commented on student papers in their subject areas and participated in workshops led by students. Topics covered were: Stance and indexicality; Sociolinguistics and multilingualism; Discourse in context; Children and sociolinguistics; Sociophonetics and gender. On the remaining day, PhD students at Edinburgh devised workshop activities and led discussion groups exploring issues in planning and funding a sociolinguistics PhD; collecting and analysing data; and moving forward on completion of the PhD. Social and cultural events for visitors were organised out of Summer School hours on Day 3 and Day 5. On the final day, a Russian film on the sociolinguistics of endangered languages was screened and discussed. ESRC support enabled all participants to attend free of cost.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>31452</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:collaborationOutput><gtr:collaboratingOrganisation>University of Glasgow</gtr:collaboratingOrganisation><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:description>Sociolinguistics Summer School student partnerships</gtr:description><gtr:id>276D9A29-4DAE-40D4-9D00-89323A1F579A</gtr:id><gtr:impact>The summer schools sometimes produce proceedings but the lasting impact of the collaborations are interpersonal and take the form of varied research partnerships which we cannot keep track of from this distance.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>56e10a676ce1e2.13812195-1</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partnerContribution>The continued vitality of the sociolinguistics summer schools has deepened networks for PG students across Europe and exposed them to a wide range of cutting edge researchers.</gtr:partnerContribution><gtr:piContribution>The Summer Schools in Sociolinguistics moved to Glasgow in 2011 and have since gone on to be held at the University of Newcastle, University College Dublin, Trinity College Dublin, and in 2016 will be held in Lyon (France). It is safe to say that the funding for the SSS in Edinburgh in 2010 helped consolidate the position of this event on the post-graduate calendar improving and advancing sociolinguistic training and networking throughout Europe.
Anecdotally we also know that the SSS 2010 established research partnerships and mentoring relationships between many of the students and faculty who attended. For example, students have gone on to work with staff at the University of Pittsburgh, staff have written letters of recommendation for several of the participants, and students who attended still write to staff asking for advice and comments on research programmes in places like Russia more than five years after the summer school was held.</gtr:piContribution><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2010-01-01</gtr:start></gtr:collaborationOutput></gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>41ED163B-FBAE-4DBB-8846-CE1393AD370E</gtr:id><gtr:title>Proceedings of the Summer School of Sociolinguistics 2010</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/9b78ac106781f99b9024d73dadc17f96"><gtr:id>9b78ac106781f99b9024d73dadc17f96</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Miriam Meyerhoff</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>546175121be949.12363254</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/H008020/1</gtr:identifier><gtr:identifier type="RES">RES-810-21-0068</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>B94A2498-60DA-4055-A957-686B6CB42654</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Linguistics</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>28710E94-8B47-404A-BD40